<p><span class="fw">1806</span>
</p>
<p>July</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">at a certain distance from the camp to keep watch.  I suffered much from the want of good water to drink.  As for the Indians they can drink stinking Stagnated water as I would drink spruce beer.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Thursday 24<sup>th</sup></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Every thing even the horses were quiet all night<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  At day break we were up.  The Old general mounted his Stud<span class="AddHand-editors">[,]</span> passed through the camp haranguing as usual all hands to muster and we moved forward<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The <span style="text-decoration:underline;">two Crows</span> always in front with the ceremonious pipe Stem which he held projected in a manner that nothing could touch it<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  At 7 just as our Van had gained the summit of the hill it began to rain very hard<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  The old chief ordered a general halt and we dismounted all cov<span class="DelHand-author">ed</span><span class="AddHand-author">ring</span> themselves from the rain as well as they could with robes, saddles &amp;<sup>c</sup>.  Such of the Young men as were finely dressed stripped themselves naked bundled their Clothes and sat upon them quietly with a view to preserve them from damage &amp; from getting wet<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  About this time word was brought to the chief that a party of the mandanes had disobeyed orders and who to escape notice were making a circuit among the hills.  Enraged at this Conduct the Chief</p>
<p style="text-align:right;">Caught</p>

